article.description: Chasity Melvin matched her career high with 30 points to help keep the Mystics' playoff hopes alive with an 82-69 overtime victory over New York.
article.headline: Melvin scores 30 as Mystics take N.Y. in overtime
article.linkText: Mystics keep playoff hopes alive with win
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chasity Melvin matched her career-high with 30
points and grabbed nine rebounds to help keep the Washington
Mystics' WNBA playoff hopes alive with an 82-69 overtime victory
Tuesday night over the New York Liberty.

Washington scored the first five points in overtime on a layup
by Melvin and a 3-pointer by Charlotte Smith-Taylor. The Mystics
were perfect on 12 free throws in the remainder of overtime to
secure the victory and end a five-game losing streak.

The Detroit Shock, who lost to the Charlotte Sting, and the
Mystics (15-17) are tied for the fourth and final playoff spot in
the Eastern Conference. Both teams have two games remaining, with a
showdown between the Shock and Mystics set for Saturday night in
Washington.

Vickie Johnson scored 18 points to lead the playoff-bound
Liberty (18-14), who had won five straight games.

Johnson hit a 3-pointer that pulled the Liberty into a tie at 63
with 1:03 remaining in regulation. Melvin missed a turnaround
jumper for Washington with 37 seconds left.

Crystal Robinson lost the handle on the ball and stepped out of
bounds on the sideline with 8.2 seconds left to give the Mystics
another possession.

Alana Beard, who scored nine points on 3-for-18 shooting, missed
a 15-foot jumper with 3 seconds left. Becky Hammon rebounded for
New York and called a timeout with less than a second to go. But
the Liberty failed to get a shot off before the horn sounded ending
regulation.

Milton-Jones had 13 points and seven rebounds for the Mystics,
who got 11 points and five assists from rookie Temeka Johnson.
Reserve Coco Miller sparked Washington with seven rebounds in 18
minutes.

After Vickie Johnson's 3-pointer from the corner gave the
Liberty a 58-57 lead, Miller responded with an offensive rebound
and basket that put the Mystics ahead. Milton-Jones made a steal on
the ensuing inbounds play and scored on a layup to give Washington
a 61-58 lead with 3:33 remaining.

Neither team led by more than four points in the first half.
Washington was in front 35-31 at the break.

Melvin's career night came on 12-for-19 shooting.
